#   SUBS-007: `be head` omits sub working-tree dirty state (LANDED)

*MEDIUM — LANDED `3ab50efd` (2026-06-06).*  Fixed in `beagle/BE.cli.c`
`behead_recurse_cb`: after relaying the sub's committed `be head ?` diff it
now also relays the sub's bare status via `BERelaySub(..., {NULL,NULL})` (the
same read-only path bare `be` uses, path-prefixed; a clean sub returns
`*NONE`), so a dirtied sub file now adds a `mod`/`dirty` line.  Repro
`test/head/21-sub-dirty-reported` added (off `WILL_FAIL`); the head/04
false-positive was tightened to require a `mod`/`dirty` marker.

*MEDIUM.*  Submodules.mkd line 20 promises `be head` recurses pre-order
"reporting ahead/behind AND dirty state per sub".  In practice `be head`'s
per-sub section only ever lists committed ahead/behind; its output is
*byte-identical* whether or not a sub file is dirty — no `dirty`/`mod`/`clean`
keyword appears anywhere.  The information is reachable (bare `be`, the status
path, DOES relay the sub's `mod core.c`), it is simply not wired into HEAD's
per-sub report.

##  Repro
 1. `be get <parent>?master`.
 2. `be head '?' > clean.out`.
 3. Append a line to `vendor/sub/core.c`.
 4. `be head '?' > dirty.out`; `diff clean.out dirty.out` → *empty*.

##  Secondary: head/04 is a false-positive test
`test/head/04-sub-dirty` PASSES, but only because it greps the combined output
for `core.c`, which appears in HEAD's committed ahead/behind file list (`+
core.c`) regardless of the dirty edit.  It does not actually exercise the
dirty-state contract it documents.  The new `test/head/21-sub-dirty-reported`
asserts the real contract (diff must change) and is `WILL_FAIL` until fixed.

##  Expected
A dirtied sub file changes the per-sub HEAD report (a `mod`/`dirty` line, as
bare `be` already produces in the status path).

##  Fix sketch
Wire HEAD's per-sub aggregation to include the sub's working-tree status (reuse
the bare-`be` status relay that already surfaces `mod core.c`), not only the
committed pin-vs-trunk ahead/behind.  Then correct head/04 (or fold it into
head/21) so it fails when dirty state is absent.

##  Tests
`test/head/21-sub-dirty-reported` (`WILL_FAIL` until fixed).

